e, its risks and associated costs. The report concludes that, because climate change is a serious global threat, the benefits of taking strong and timely action are more important than the economic costs of not taking action. Stern, N. (2006). The Economics of Climate Change: The Stern Review. Cabinet Office \u2013 HM Treasury. Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, UK. Retrieved from the World Wide Web from: http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/ independent_reviews/stern_review_economics_ climate_change/sternreview_index.cfm 238 2. Climate change and gender Reference Description Concise bulletin that covers the most pressing matters for developing countries insofar as they adapt to climate change. UK Parliamentary Office of Science and Technology. (2006). Adapting to Climate Change in Developing Countries. Retrieved from the World Wide Web from: http://www. parliament.uk/documents/upload/postpn269. pdf The Kyoto Protocol of the UNFCCC is an amendment to the international treaty on climate change that obliges signatory nations to reduce emissions. It entered into force on 16 February 2005. United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (UNFCCC). (2005). The Kyoto Protocol.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ee7d9d23-8233-4ff8-93a0-983b5c2d5c09": {"__data__": {"id_": "ee7d9d23-8233-4ff8-93a0-983b5c2d5c09", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/training-manual-gender-and-climate-change", "Author": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Publisher": "International Union for Conservation of Nature", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Training manual on gender and climate change", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.iucn.org/resources/grey-literature/